Well, It seems my husband managed to beat me to posting.

Yes, I have a contract job. The frist part was 40 hours (apx of work), and they paid 1/2 up front, when I could deminstrate a proof of concept on Monday. The Project will be finished on next Tues, a few days early.

Project A - Simple, work around for solution, and a Data Interperation system.
Project B - Pulling the data directly from the system, and doing all the processing in the excel program directly, to allow greater scale up of resources

Project C - Automating a system.

After saving a chunkc back for taxes, I'll be making more a week than I was at my old job. Which is fitting, as I was SERIOUSLY underpaid. And they knew it.

When I get project B done... We talk long term. I will likly be signing a 1-5 year contract, to work exclusinvly for them. Which means, I have a home office. And working from home means all sorts of things.

Even if it dosn't pan out, this project should get me a good 3K for the house fund.

Oh - and the Owner is pretty cool. He buys breakfast at all early morning meetings. And when I mentioned I would be buying Office 2007 with the 1/2 payment on project B, he BOUGHT a copy for me to use. That was cool.

Right now, I'm sitting and watching the second system test complete. When that's done, I go home and start on the other three parts of this.

Tues, 10 am, Supposed to meet them with a done project.

I LOVE being able to work again.

Not that someone is getting up and preaching this. But that an evangelical preacher is standing up and saying these things, despite losing a fifth of his church and despite the pressure to conform to the "normal" ideas for that sect.

My parents are religious. They love their new church, attend most weekends they are in town, and drag me with them when I visit. They are also extremely democratic and fixtures at the local party events.

Faith dose not make you Republican. Faith is between you and God, and in how you live your life. Politics shouldn't matter.

A person with a lawful good attitude believes in the use of authority and rule of law to bring good to the greatest number of people. Her/His actions support the status quo and s/he uses systems and organizations to achieve good goals.

S/He will keep his/her word and value truth.
S/He will avoid the use of poison and use violence only when authorized to do so or in self defense.
S/He may or may not be disciplined, organized, emotionally restrained, caring, compassionate, and peaceful, but s/he believes that these are admirable qualities.
Respects law and order and is willing to suffer limitations on individual freedom for the benefit of the group.
Puts moral principles before material considerations.
The lawful good person will be a very faithful member of a group, but if the laws of the group clash with the ethics dictated by his or her moral alignment, the lawful good person will probably leave that group and look for a group more closely aligned with his or her ethics.
The lawful good person is an active advocate of his or her beliefs.

Lawful Good "Saintly"
"Crusader"

A lawful good [person] upholds society and its laws, believing that these laws are created to work for the good and prosperity of all. He is both honest and benevolent. He will work within the established system to change it for the better, and strives to bring order to goodness that other good-aligned [people] might pool their resources to better the world. A lawful good [person] combines a commitment to oppose evil with discipline. Most lawful good [people] live by a strict code of honor, or by the rules of conduct set down by their deity. They will generally selflessly act by these codes even at the cost of their own life.

Lawful good combines honor and compassion for the innocent.

A knight/paladin who always follows the orders of his superiors is an example of a lawful good [person].

I haven't been taling much in LJ for a lot of reasons. Until I saw this, which is a good idea on so many levels. Borrowed from the March was not a happy month for many people. In fact, 2007 to-date has seemed determined to be the year of bad emotional shit. So I'm suggesting something different for today. Be a different kind of fool -- a springtime fool. A Tarot Fool. Start the journey fresh, with a leap off the cliff not of trickery, but hope. Do something positive, something that brings a smile. For yourself, for someone else. Make it small, or huge, planned or impulsive. But do it quietly, without fanfare, for the simple act of bringing joy. And spread the word.
